Document: Ray Casting
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/ray-casting.rst
Summary: This section explains how to exclude specific colliders, like the caster itself, from ray cast results using the `exclude` property of `PhysicsRayQueryParameters2D`.

When performing ray casting, a common scenario is for a character to gather information about its surroundings. A potential issue arises because the character itself has a collider, which the ray might detect first, preventing it from identifying objects further away. This is known as self-intersection.

To prevent the ray from colliding with its own collider, the `intersect_ray()` method accepts an array of exceptions through its `exclude` property. This property can be set using either the node itself or its RID.

Here's an example of how to implement this exclusion in GDScript for a `CharacterBody2D`:

GDScript:
```gdscript
extends CharacterBody2D

func _physics_process(delta):
    var space_state = get_world_2d().direct_space_state
    var query = PhysicsRayQueryParameters2D.create(global_position, player_position)
    query.exclude = [self]
    var result = space_state.intersect_ray(query)
```

And here's the equivalent in C#:

C#:
```csharp
using Godot;

public partial class MyCharacterBody2D : CharacterBody2D
{
    public override void _PhysicsProcess(double delta)
    {
        var spaceState = GetWorld2D().DirectSpaceSpaceState;
        var query = PhysicsRayQueryParameters2D.Create(globalPosition, playerPosition);
        query.Exclude = [GetRid()];
        var result = spaceState.IntersectRay(query);
    }
}
```

The `exclude` array can contain either node objects or their corresponding Resource IDs (RIDs).
---CHUNK---
Document: Ray Casting
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/ray-casting.rst
Summary: This section explains how to use collision masks with ray casting in Godot to efficiently manage exceptions.

The collision mask system provides a more efficient way to handle a large or dynamic list of exceptions compared to the exceptions method. The `intersect_ray()` parameters object can accept a collision mask. To use the same mask as the parent body, you can utilize the `collision_mask` member variable. The array of exceptions can still be provided as the last argument.

GDScript:
```gdscript
extends CharacterBody2D

func _physics_process(delta):
    var space_state = get_world_2d().direct_space_state
    var query = PhysicsRayQueryParameters2D.create(global_position, target_position,
        collision_mask, [self])
    var result = space_state.intersect_ray(query)
```

C#:
```csharp
using Godot;

public partial class MyCharacterBody2D : CharacterBody2D
{
    public override void _PhysicsProcess(double delta)
    {
        var spaceState = GetWorld2D().DirectSpaceState;
        var query = PhysicsRayQueryParameters2D.Create(globalPosition, targetPosition,
            CollisionMask, [GetRid()]);
        var result = spaceState.IntersectRay(query);
    }
}
```

For more information on setting the collision mask, refer to the collision layer/mask example.
---CHUNK---
Document: 3D ray casting from screen
Path: godot/tutorials/physics/ray-casting.rst
Summary: This section explains how to cast a ray from the screen into the 3D physics space for object picking using a Camera3D node.

Casting a ray from screen to 3D physics space is useful for object picking. While CollisionObject3D has an "input_event" signal for this purpose, manual ray casting can be done using a Camera3D node. A Camera3D can be in perspective or orthogonal projection modes, requiring the calculation of both ray origin and direction.

To obtain the ray origin and direction using a camera, the following code can be used:

GDScript:
    const RAY_LENGTH = 1000.0

    func _input(event):
        if event is InputEventMouseButton and event.pressed and event.button_index == 1:
            var camera3d = $Camera3D
            var from = camera3d.project_ray_origin(event.position)
            var to = from + camera3d.project_ray_normal(event.position) * RAY_LENGTH

C#:
    private const float RayLength = 1000.0f;

    public override void _Input(InputEvent @event)
    {
        if (@event is InputEventMouseButton eventMouseButton && eventMouseButton.Pressed && eventMouseButton.ButtonIndex == MouseButton.Left)
        {
            var camera3D = GetNode<Camera3D>("Camera3D");
            var from = camera3D.ProjectRayOrigin(eventMouseButton.Position);
            var to = from + camera3D.ProjectRayNormal(eventMouseButton.Position) * RayLength;
        }
    }

Key Rule: During _input(), the physics space may be locked, so ray casting queries should typically be run in _physics_process().